revision.text:
#describe the models of the Universe as proposed by Copernicus and Kepler. &#10004;
#describe the progress in the understanding of the Universe as a result of the work of Copernicus, Kepler and Galileo. &#10004;
#use Newton’s law of Gravitation to derive an expression for the radius of the circular orbit of a planet around the Sun in terms of the period of the orbit. &#10004;
#recall and use Kepler’s laws as applied to circular orbits. &#10004;
#recall how the existence of Neptune was predicted from the orbit of Uranus. &#10004;
#appreciate the significance of Kepler’s third law as evidence of Newton’s law of Gravitation. &#10004;
#describe the contents of the Solar System in terms of the Sun, planets, planetary satellites and comets. Details of individual planets are not required.&#10004;
#show awareness of the principal contents of the Universe, including stars, galaxies and radiation. '''Probably better to cover this in Stars & Galaxies'''
#define distances measured in astronomical units (AU), parsecs (pc) and light-years.&#10004;
#recall the approximate magnitudes, in metres, of the AU, pc and light-year.&#10004;
#recall the distances involved between objects in the Universe, including distance to nearest stars, distance across a galaxy, size of observable Universe. '''Probably better to cover this in Stars & Galaxies'''
#appreciate the range of magnitudes of the sizes and masses of objects in the Universe. '''Probably better to cover this in Stars & Galaxies'''

{{stub}}
The English word ''algol'' comes from Arabic al ghûl. The Arabian ghoul is a desert-dwelling, shape-shifting demon that robs graves and feeds on the dead. Ghouls lure travelers into the desert wastes to devour them.  The star Beta Persei, commonly known as Algol, is named after this creature.  All things considered, an appropriate name for a progamming language.

