{{Java:boolean}} is a [[Java Programming/Keywords|keyword]] which designates the
{{Java:boolean}} [[Java Programming/Primitive Types|primitive type]].
There are only two possible {{Java:boolean}} values: {{Java:true}} and {{Java:false}}.
The default value for {{Java:boolean}} fields is {{Java:false}}.

The following is a declaration of a {{Java:private}} {{Java:boolean}} field named <code>initialized</code>, and its use in a method named <code>synchronized</code>. {{java|code=
private boolean initialized = false; 
public synchronized void {
   if ( !initialized ) {
      connection = connect();
      initialized = true;
   }
}
}}

Note that there is no automatic conversion between integer types (such as {{Java:int}})
to {{Java:boolean}} as is possible in some languages like [[Programming C|C]].
Instead, one must use an equivalent expression such as <code>(i != 0)</code> which evaluates
to {{Java:true}} if <code>i</code> is not zero.

[[Category:Java Programming/Keywords]]
[[Category:Java Programming]]

{{Java:public}} is a Java [[Java Programming/Keywords|keyword]] which declares a member's [[Java Programming/Scope|access]] as public. Public members are visible to all other classes. This means that any other class can access a {{Java:public}} field or method. Further, other classes can modify {{Java:public}} fields unless the field is declared as {{Java:final}}.

A best practice is to give fields {{Java:private}} access and reserve {{Java:public}} access to only the set of methods and {{Java:final}} fields that define the class' public constants. This helps with encapsulation and information hiding, since it allows you to change the implementation of a class without affecting the consumers who use only the public API of the class.

Below is an example of an immutable {{Java:public}} class named <code>Length</code> which maintains {{Java:private}} instance fields named <code>units</code> and <code>magnitude</code> but provides a {{Java:public}} constructor and two {{Java:public}} accessor methods.

{{XCode|1=<span id="code-listing-1">'''Code listing: Length.java'''</span>
<syntaxhighlight lang="Java5" line start="1" highlight="4, 5, 16-18, 20-22">
package org.wikibooks.java;

public class Length {
   private double magnitude;
   private String units;

   public Length(double magnitude, String units) {
      if ((units == null) || (units.trim().length() == 0)) {
          throw new IllegalArgumentException("non-null, non-empty units required.");
      }

      this.magnitude = magnitude;
      this.units = units;
   }

   public double getMagnitude() {
      return magnitude;
   }

   public String getUnits() {
      return units;
   }
}
</syntaxhighlight>}}
[[Category:Java Programming/Keywords]]
[[Category:Java Programming]]

